Identifier (or) Variable declration:

A Tcl identifier is a name used to identify a variable, function, or any other user-defined 
item. An identifier starts with a letter A to Z or a to z or an underscore (_) followed by 
zero or more letters, underscores, dollars ($), and digits (0 to 9).

A variable is created automatically when you assign a value to it using the set command.

syntax: 
set Variable_name value

examples:
set Name AjaykumarBurada   ;# value ---> AjaykumarBurada is assign to Variable_name ----> Name
set Age 24     ;# value ----> 24 is assign to Variable_name ----> Age
set Professional "PD Engineer"
puts $Name ;#   $----> dollar symbol is used to display the value of Name
puts $Age
puts $Professional


Substitutions:

1. Command Substitution:
In command substitutions, square brackets are used to evaluate the scripts inside the square brackets. 
A simple example to add two numbers is shown below:

puts [expr 1 + 6 + 9]
puts [list ajay kumar burada]


2. Variable substitution:
In variable substitutions, $ is used before the variable name and this returns the contents of the variable. 
A simple example to set a value to a variable and print it is shown below.

set a 5
set b 10

puts $a
puts $b
puts [expr $a * $b] ;#command substitution

3. Backslash Substituiton:
These are commonly called escape sequences; with each backslash, followed by a letter having its own meaning. 
A simple example for newline substitution is shown below:

puts "Hello\nWorld" ;# \n is new line
puts "Line 1\nLine 2\tTabbed"  ;# \t is tab
puts "Quote: \"Hello World\"" ;# " " is inverted commas


#### combination of both variable and substitution  ####

Example 1:

set variableA "10"
puts $variableA
set sum [expr $variableA +20];

Example 2:
set variableA 10
set {variable B} test
puts $variableA
puts ${variable B}

#### mathematical expression in variable & substitution  ####

Example 1:
set variableA "10"
set result [expr $variableA / 9];
puts $result
set result [expr $variableA / 9.0];
puts $result
set variableA "10.0"
set result [expr $variableA / 9];
puts $result

Example 2:

set variableA "10"
set tcl_precision 5
set result [expr $variableA / 9.0];
puts $result
